Maternal Child Systems Change — OPEN A.R.M.S.

Systems Branch Knowledge Base

Purpose of This Repository

The Systems branch houses the full systems‑level architecture, policy framework, and implementation infrastructure for the Maternal Child Systems Change with OPEN A.R.M.S. initiative.

This knowledge base is designed for:

• Policymakers
• Funders
• Healthcare partners
• Child welfare agencies
• Researchers
• Implementation teams
• Cross‑sector collaborators


It provides a comprehensive, structured, and replicable model for statewide maternal‑child transformation.

---

What This Knowledge Base Contains

This branch organizes the OPEN A.R.M.S. systems model into clear, functional domains:

1. Overview

High‑level orientation to the OPEN A.R.M.S. model, including the executive summary, systems overview, and guiding principles.

2. Policy & Advocacy

Policy briefs, legislative talking points, systems gap analyses, and federal alignment maps (HRSA, SAMHSA, DOJ, CMS).

3. Clinical Model & Standards

The midwifery‑inclusive, WHNP‑led, CNM‑supported clinical framework, including care pathways, Centering Pregnancy integration, and trauma‑informed labor standards.

4. Systems Architecture

Referral pathways, interagency coordination models, data flow diagrams, and statewide maternal‑child systems infrastructure.

5. Implementation Playbooks

Operational guides for launching, scaling, and sustaining OPEN A.R.M.S. sites, including staffing models, training frameworks, and quality assurance.

6. Evaluation & Outcomes

Logic models, KPIs, data collection tools, and evaluation frameworks for continuous improvement and accountability.

7. Communications & External Relations

Messaging guides, one‑pagers, slide decks, MOUs, and public‑facing materials for partners and stakeholders.

---

How to Use This Repository

This knowledge base is structured to support:

• Policy development
• Program replication
• Cross‑agency coordination
• Grant writing and federal alignment
• Clinical integration
• Systems‑level decision‑making
• Training and onboarding


Each folder contains standalone documents that can be used independently or as part of the full systems model.

---

Guiding Principles

The OPEN A.R.M.S. systems model is built on:

• Maternal autonomy & dignity
• Midwifery‑inclusive care
• Trauma‑informed practice
• Family preservation
• Cross‑sector collaboration
• Evidence‑based decision‑making
• Scalability & sustainability


---

Intended Impact

This knowledge base supports the development of a statewide maternal‑child system that:

• Reduces maternal morbidity
• Expands access to prenatal and behavioral health care
• Prevents unnecessary newborn foster care placements
• Strengthens family stability
• Improves long‑term maternal and infant outcomes
• Creates a replicable model for national adoption


